Poland and space.
Last week, a meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency of Poland was adopted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second member of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the years that followed, it actively participated in a number of agency projects.
But Poland's path to space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space voyages, but that was not always understood.
I recall, for example, a lecture by A. Sternfeld, who presented the ideas of his innovative work, “Introduce into space,” at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933.
The ideas of a young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Stternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Hadodomsky had an interest in his work.
In 1934, in France, Stternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry Award and André Luis Hirsch Award for "Introduction to Space Science".
Dr. Jan Hadodomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great advocate of astronomy and space science.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadovsky became a world-renowned space propagandist, and his contribution was appreciated, including the fact that one of the craters on the back of the moon was named after him.
By 1925, a railway sawmill had been built in Poland, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket was to be used for the race or for the towing of a calf.
The information on this outfit is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, Polish artillery has begun to think about rocket launchers.
The study was carried out by the Armed Technology Section in collaboration with Professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzitzki.
The remaining materials show that the studies have reached the practical test stage.
But with the German troops coming, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the specialized press came up with the idea of a photoelectric fighter rocket proposed by Rogosinski, and the work of the author Léliva-Kzivoblocski, Air Torpedo Missile and Air Bomb, came out next year.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
The Interim Scientific and Advisory Committee (Temporary Advisory and Scientific Committee) coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of its work it was completed because of the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work on space science appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society.
For the first time, society is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problems, which publishes four large articles on astronautism.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovic suggested organizing a space-based society.
At the time, the projects of artificial satellites were already being developed, and space research was clear to be a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (POA) has tried to join the international Federation of Astronauticalism (founded in 1951), and has become a real member of the Polish PLA in autumn.
The following year, the first president, Kazimezh Zarankevich (1902-1959), became Vice-President of the International Federation of Astronauticals.
He remained in that position until his death, which came in 1959.
Since 1956, PAA has made a significant contribution to the very successful meteorological missile RM (Rakieta Meteorological), which became the first Polish missile to carry out scientific research.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and the first launch was held on 10 October 1958.
A missile capable of overcoming a distance of 1800 metres was about 80 cm long and weighing less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of RM-1A was built and two-step RM-2 rocket tests were conducted in the summer of 1959.
The rocket was approximately 1.4 metres long, with a weight of approximately 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to do the present scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could have been over 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high wind.
But further development was suspended in 1962.
The first RM-type missile was inherited by Meteor-1, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-step, its total length was 510 cm and its initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (defined as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the space for scientific equipment.
Meteor-1A had an area of 0.4 l, Meteor-1B - 0.34 l and Meteor-1C - 0.62 l.
The maximum flight distance of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aviation Institute developed the Meteor-2 rocket and began its first flight tests in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a starting weight of 380 kg was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg at a height of about 60 km.
The versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were then built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland ' s accession to COSPAR (the Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the National Committee of COSPAR two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space studies on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslav Hermashewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
