Saba: “Germany should play a more important role”
Germany abstained in the vote to recognize Palestine.
In Stephen Sabo's view, the US-Europe liaison expert, in this way, Berlin balances on the narrow diplomatic track.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany initially made it clear that it would vote against Palestinian applications for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli action in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I do not believe that the American position is supportive either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
Germany also abstained in a vote to establish a no-fly zone during the June 2011 Libya uprising.
As a result, NATO has made this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
The point is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, that is, from a policy that the United States, to its own German foreign policy, has ruled.
The situation is further complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have an agreed common policy.
Thus, the Germans are again between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that as long as they only get their part, they're on their way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy that France or Britain is pursuing.
What exactly does “normal” external policy mean in German terms?
This willingness to take a position that is independent of the position of the United States or European partners in their national interest.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policies, i.e. exports and links with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany ' s economic interests differ greatly from those of other major States, and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Did these economic interests affect the position of the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has major markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
It therefore needs to be careful not to insult the public and the elite in Arab countries.
Either way, it's playing a role.
But I wouldn't attach too much importance to it, it's not a completely unilateral relationship.
But in any case, this plays an important role in the German calculations.
Did Germany damage its relations with the United States by refraining from making important decisions, such as the Palestinian vote?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States, there is an understanding of the German position.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as the Libyan question.
Germany may even gain some respect in this way.
This indicates that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be considered.
There are various views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
On the contrary, the United States had made a clear statement in favour of the veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European States?
Because of American domestic policy, there have always been such differences.
I believe that the Obama Government has a sufficient understanding of the European position.
However, in the context of the local political situation, the Government cannot, of course, take such an open stand.
I believe that substantial differences of opinion are not as significant as it always seems.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all pleased with Netanyahu's policy.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of the EU's most important partner on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a single, non-controversial European policy, but now it is not.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and are forced to act instead, based only on their own vision of the situation.
That's how they do with the euro.
I think that in the future, Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position.
Clearly, it is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
The subject has always been sensitive.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany itself sees itself as an important international player, would it not really play a major role?
Or is it still difficult for Germany to take the lead?
Germany has not yet gotten used to this, it is still always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still hard to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis, each time Germany assumes an important role, there are a wide range of anti-German feelings.
It's not just the Germans to deal with it.
In fact, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It should take into account a wide range of neighbours and views, and that is not easy.
So, the U.S. influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at this point the EU is not filling this vacuum, but who is then remaining?
Germans will simply have to play a larger role.
Even if you don't like it, it doesn't feel good or it makes you feel unloved, it's life!
Stephen Sabo, Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., where academics and political experts from Europe and North America are working together to study the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Sabo is a member of the Marshall German Foundation, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
